  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some extracurricular activities I could do to improve my chances at getting into Ivy League schools?",
  "response": "Getting into Ivy League schools is highly competitive, and extracurricular activities can play a significant role in your application. Here are some activities that can help improve your chances:\n\n1. **Leadership Roles**: Demonstrating leadership is crucial. Aim to hold positions such as president, captain, or founder in clubs, sports teams, or organizations.\n\n2. **Academic Clubs**: Participate in academic clubs such as debate, math club, science club, or Model United Nations. These show your intellectual curiosity and commitment to academic excellence.\n\n3. **Community Service**: Engage in meaningful community service projects. Consider volunteering at local charities, hospitals, or schools, or initiating your own community service project.\n\n4. **Research Projects**: Get involved in scientific research or independent studies. Collaborate with local universities or professors to work on research projects, and aim to publish your findings.\n\n5. **Arts and Music**: If you have talents in visual arts, music, theater, or dance, actively pursue these interests. Join school bands, orchestras, art clubs, or theater productions.\n\n6. **Sports**: Participate in sports and aim for varsity-level involvement. Demonstrating dedication to a sport shows commitment and teamwork.\n\n7. **Internships**: Seek internships or part-time work related to your field of interest. Gaining practical experience can set you apart from other applicants.\n\n8. **Competitions and Awards**: Compete in academic, artistic, or athletic competitions at regional, national, or international levels. Winning awards can significantly bolster your application.\n\n9. **Public Speaking and Writing**: Engage in activities that enhance your public speaking and writing skills, such as joining the debate team or writing for the school newspaper.\n\n10. **Cultural Organizations**: Join or start cultural clubs, promoting diversity and cultural exchange. This shows your commitment to broadening your horizons and engaging with different perspectives.\n\n11. **Entrepreneurship**: If you have a knack for business, start your own venture or participate in entrepreneurship programs or competitions.\n\n12. **STEM Activities**: Engage in science, technology, engineering, and math-related activities, such as robotics clubs, coding camps, or science fairs.\n\nRemember, depth and dedication in a few activities often impress admissions committees more than superficial involvement in many. Focus on your passions and seek to make a meaningful impact.",
